1120 S Cady Mall</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>INDTDSB 366</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Tempe</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>AZ</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>85282</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>United States</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/D4D3ABDE-9DCF-4F10-B04F-A2F337535CE7"><gtr:id>D4D3ABDE-9DCF-4F10-B04F-A2F337535CE7</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Padraig</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Gleeson</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G90%2F100"><gtr:id>1E1D1A5F-0C8C-4907-ABF7-F745FD85EE4D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Investigation of signal processing in the cerebellar cortex with a biologically realistic 3D neural network model</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G90/100</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>In this study I will use computer simulations to investigate how information is processed in a part of the brain involved in the control of movement (the cerebellum). The cerebellum is an attractive brain region for this type of study because it has a relatively simple anatomy and the behaviours of the cell types are well characterized. The study will focus on how the cell shapes, number of connections and the mechanisms underlying the transmission of electrical impulses at neuronal connections (synapses) determine how information is processed in this brain region. Since the software tools available for this type of question are rather limited, a key component of this study will be to develop new software for constructing biologically realistic 3D neural network models and for analysing their electrical behaviour. This will allow an accurate 3D representation of the cerebellar cortex to be generated from measurements from real cells. Constructing more accurate and realistic computational simulations of the brain will lead to a better understanding of the complex processes that underlie brain function in health and in disease.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Electrophysiological, anatomical and imaging experiments have revealed a number of synaptic and cellular processes that are thought to be involved in the processing of information in the brain. However, little is know about the role particular mechanisms play in signal processing. In this study I will investigate, with computer simulations, the contribution that cellular mechanisms and cellular anatomy make to signal processing in the cerebellar cortex. The cerebellum lends itself to the investigation of signal processing because it has a regular structure consisting of a few, well characterized, cell types. Moreover, a wealth of data exists on the electrophysiological properties and morphology of the cells in this region. 

Software tools will be developed that will allow the construction of realistic 3D models of this brain region based on the anatomical and physiological data This software will extend the Neuron simulation package, a tool which is widely used in the field at present for modelling single neurons and simple networks. These new computational tools will enable much more complex networks to be constructed, and will allow various experimentally determined parameters to be specified (e.g. number of synaptic connections between different types of cell, distributions of dendrite length, etc). Software will also be developed to analyze and visualize network activity. The software created during this study will be Open Source, and will be made freely available to the neuroscience community, in the hope that it can be used in modelling other brain regions. 

Both dendritic and axonal morphology are believed to be important determinants of neuronal processing. However, cell-to-cell variability in these structures has been ignored in most network models to date. We will look at how variations in the shapes of cells and the number of synaptic connections influence signal processing in a cerebellar network. Another key area will be to investigate how shunting inhibition and the different spatial and temporal properties of presynaptic modulation influence the spatio-temporal properties of activity in the network. These investigations will link in with experimental work currently taking place in the host lab, and will provide a simulation framework in which to test theories of signal processing in the cerebellar cortex.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-14</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-09-15</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>240261</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Arizona State University</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United States of America</gtr:country><gtr:description>NeuroML initiative</gtr:description><gtr:id>3F997E77-FA68-437C-A61B-717AA9716AD2</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The full list of applications which support this language are available here: http://www.neuroml.org/tool_support.php, and our lab has been instrumental in ensuring support for NeuroML in many of these packages.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>CEE7D4FBE54-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:piContribution>The main recipient of the grant is currently one of the main contributors to the NeuroML model description language (http://www.neuroml.org/index.php), which seeks to create a format for exchanging complex models of the nervous system between researchers and software applications.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>1000000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Biomedical Resources</gtr:description><gtr:end>2013-10-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Wellcome Trust</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>08A82ED4-B242-4DE1-A387-C6CEFCF2485B</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>1DB105110640</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2008-11-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>Open Source Software. Freely available at http://www.neuroconstruct.org</gtr:description><gtr:id>D90123C6-7FEC-4597-8F91-E887B905BD01</gtr:id><gtr:impact>There have been approximately 1200 registered user downloads of the software from 40+ countries since 2007</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>E62645F267B</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>neuroConstruct</gtr:title><gtr:type>Improvements to research infrastructure</gtr:type><gtr:url>http://www.neuroconstruct.org</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2007</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>DB477D13-3E12-4865-8186-BFB1D2D7D4C0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Interoperability of neuroscie